INSERT INTO contributions (idea_id, author_id, content, decision_log, status, view_count, submitted_at, created_at, updated_at) VALUES
(11, 15, E'# ChairFill \x2014 Predictive Dental Recall & Schedule Optimization\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nChairFill takes a data-science approach to dental recall: instead of blasting every patient with the same reminder sequence, it uses a predictive no-show score to triage outreach effort. High-risk patients get a phone call plus SMS plus email; low-risk patients get a single text. The result is a 40\xe2\x80\x9350% reduction in front-desk recall labor while simultaneously improving chair utilization by filling high-risk slots earlier. Built for independent dental practices with 500\xe2\x80\x932,000 patients, ChairFill integrates with the three major practice management systems and delivers an ROI dashboard that shows the dentist exactly how many dollars were recovered each month.\n\n**Differentiation from generic recall tools**: ChairFill does not send the same message to every patient. It learns which patients actually show up when reminded by text vs. phone, and adjusts automatically.\n\n**Year-1 Goals**:\n- 300 practices enrolled\n- Average 42% reduction in no-show rate\n- MRR of $72,000 by month 12\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Data | Notes |\n|--------|------|-------|\n| US independent dental practices | ~107,000 | ADA 2023 |\n| Target segment (500\xe2\x80\x932,000 patients) | ~58,000 | ~54% of market |\n| Avg hygiene chair revenue/year | $180,000\xe2\x80\x93$264,000 | 2 hygienists typical |\n| Recall no-show revenue loss/practice/year | $38K\xe2\x80\x93$52K | 18\xe2\x80\x9323% no-show rate |\n| Front-desk hours on recall calls/week | 8\xe2\x80\x9315 hrs | Primary labor cost |\n| Practices with predictive recall software | <5% | Proprietary survey N=200 |\n| TAM | ~$348M/year | 58,000 \xd7 $500/mo |\n| SAM (digitally reachable) | ~$104M/year | 30% reachable |\n| Year-1 SOM | ~$900K | 300 \xd7 $250/mo avg |\n\n**Trend**: Post-pandemic recall backlogs mean practices have 200\xe2\x80\x93400 overdue patients right now. Automated reactivation is the fastest revenue win available to practice owners.\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Product | Approach | Price/mo | Predictive Scoring | PMS Sync | Weakness |\n|---------|----------|----------|--------------------|----------|----------|\n| Lighthouse 360 | Rule-based sequences | $349\xe2\x80\x93$499 | No | Yes | No intelligence, same blast for everyone |\n| Solutionreach | Engagement suite | $400\xe2\x80\x93$600 | No | Yes | Bloated feature set, poor UX |\n| Weave | VoIP + messaging | $400\xe2\x80\x93$550 | No | Partial | Recall is an afterthought |\n| RevenueWell | Marketing automation | $299\xe2\x80\x93$450 | No | Yes | Complex campaigns, not recall-focused |\n| NexHealth | Modern patient experience | $400\xe2\x80\x93$700 | No | Yes | Broad platform, premium price |\n| **ChairFill** | **Predictive recall AI** | **$179\xe2\x80\x93$279** | **Yes** | **Yes** | **Newer brand** |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n### Persona A: Growth-Minded Practice Owner \xe2\x80\x94 Dr. James Okonkwo\n- **Age**: 41, male, owns a 3-chair practice in suburban Atlanta\n- **Patient Panel**: 1,200 active patients, 2 hygienists\n- **Pain Points**:\n  1. No-show rate of 21% is costing him ~$47,000/year\n  2. Front desk spends 3 hours/day calling patients; he pays $38K/year for that labor\n  3. Current recall software (Lighthouse 360) sends the same reminder to every patient and he doesn''t see a difference\n- **Goal**: Cut no-shows by half and free up front-desk time for insurance verification\n- **WTP**: $229\xe2\x80\x93$279/month; expects visible ROI within 45 days\n\n### Persona B: Efficiency-Focused Office Manager \xe2\x80\x94 Sandra Park\n- **Age**: 39, manages 2-location dental group in Seattle\n- **Patient Panel**: 2,800 patients across both locations\n- **Pain Points**:\n  1. Managing recall across two locations with different hygiene schedules is chaotic\n  2. No way to tell which reminder channel actually works for each patient\n  3. Her dentist-boss asks for monthly numbers she has to compile manually\n- **Goal**: Unified dashboard for both locations; auto-generated monthly ROI report\n- **WTP**: $350+/month for multi-location capability\n\n### Persona C: Retiring Dentist Selling Practice \xe2\x80\x94 Dr. Patricia Wells\n- **Age**: 59, solo practice in rural Wisconsin, 680 patients\n- **Motivation**: Wants to maximize practice valuation by reducing no-shows and demonstrating clean recall metrics before sale\n- **WTP**: $149/month, short-term engagement, values simplicity\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Feature | Priority | Description |\n|---------|----------|-------------|\n| No-show risk scoring per patient | P0 | ML model trained on appointment history, demographics, reminder response |\n| Tiered outreach automation | P0 | High-risk: phone + SMS + email; Medium: SMS + email; Low: SMS only |\n| Overdue patient queue | P0 | Auto-sorted by risk score and days overdue |\n| Real-time ROI dashboard | P0 | Monthly revenue recovered, no-show rate trend, chair utilization % |\n| PMS bi-directional sync | P1 | Dentrix, Eaglesoft, Open Dental; 15-min delta sync |\n| Cancellation backfill engine | P1 | Instant SMS to waitlist when slot opens; fills within 2 hrs on avg |\n| Two-way SMS confirmations | P1 | Patient confirms/cancels/reschedules via text |\n| Multi-location support | P1 | Unified dashboard across locations with per-location drill-down |\n| Automated voice calls | P2 | AI-generated voice for patients who don''t respond to SMS |\n| Post-visit NPS + review prompts | P2 | Auto-send satisfaction survey + Google review request |\n| Custom recall intervals by procedure | P2 | Different cadences for perio maintenance vs. standard recall |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Core Engine**: Python 3.12 + scikit-learn for the no-show prediction model. Trained on anonymized appointment history (n=50,000+ appointments from beta practices). Retrained weekly as new data comes in.\n\n**Backend API**: FastAPI (Python) for ML-heavy endpoints; Go microservice for high-throughput message delivery.\n\n**Database**: PostgreSQL 16 (HIPAA-compliant, encrypted at rest). Redis for session caching and job queues.\n\n**Messaging**: Twilio Verify for 10DLC compliance; SendGrid for email; ElevenLabs for AI voice generation.\n\n**PMS Connectors**: Plugin-based adapter architecture. Open Dental direct DB connector; Dentrix and Eaglesoft via their official REST APIs.\n\n**Infrastructure**: AWS HIPAA-eligible stack (ECS + RDS Multi-AZ + S3). SOC 2 Type II in progress.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price/Month | Locations | Patient Limit | Features |\n|------|-------------|-----------|---------------|----------|\n| Starter | $179 | 1 | 800 | Risk scoring, SMS/email recall, basic dashboard |\n| Pro | $249 | 1 | 2,000 | + Waitlist engine, voice fallback, PMS sync, ROI dashboard |\n| Multi-Site | $399 | Up to 3 | 5,000 | + Multi-location, team permissions, consolidated reporting |\n| Enterprise | Custom | Unlimited | Unlimited | DSO/group, white-label, API, dedicated support |\n\n**Add-ons**: SMS bundle overages ($0.012/msg), custom PMS integration ($75/mo), practice website widget ($29/mo).\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|-----------|----------|--------------|\n| M1 | Weeks 1\xe2\x80\x934 | Rule-based recall (before ML), SMS/email delivery, CSV patient import, HIPAA infra, basic no-show dashboard |\n| M2 | Weeks 5\xe2\x80\x938 | Open Dental PMS sync, two-way SMS, overdue patient queue, waitlist engine v1 |\n| M3 | Weeks 9\xe2\x80\x9312 | ML no-show risk model v1, tiered outreach engine, Dentrix sync, ROI dashboard |\n| M4 | Weeks 13\xe2\x80\x9316 | Eaglesoft sync, voice fallback, multi-location, self-serve billing (Stripe), onboarding wizard |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M3 Target | M12 Target |\n|-----|-----------|------------|\n| Active practices | 50 | 300 |\n| Avg no-show reduction | 30% | 42% |\n| Model accuracy (AUC-ROC) | 0.72 | 0.81 |\n| MRR | $10,500 | $72,000 |\n| Monthly churn rate | <6% | <3.5% |\n| Messages delivered within SLA | 98% | 99.5% |\n| NPS | >40 | >62 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|------|------------|--------|------------|\n| ML model underperforms with small practice data | High (early) | Medium | Start with rule-based logic; transition to ML only after 6+ months of data per practice |\n| HIPAA audit failure | Low | Critical | HIPAA-compliance consultant from day 1; separate PHI from analytics data stores |\n| PMS API deprecation | Medium | High | Maintain CSV import as permanent fallback; track vendor API roadmaps |\n| Customer distrust of AI scoring | Medium | Medium | Show prediction rationale per patient (transparent scoring); allow manual overrides |\n| Twilio 10DLC delays blocking launch | Medium | High | Begin A2P campaign registration 8 weeks before launch; test on toll-free as interim |\n| Competitor adds predictive scoring | Medium | Medium | File for patent on core scoring methodology; build switching costs via data history |',
 E'[{"step": 1, "action": "Problem framing", "rationale": "Reframed the recall problem from \x27sending reminders\x27 to \x27predicting and preventing no-shows\x27\xe2\x80\x94a more defensible and valuable position."}, {"step": 2, "action": "Competitive differentiation", "rationale": "All existing tools use rule-based sequences with no intelligence. Predictive scoring is a clear white space."}, {"step": 3, "action": "ML feasibility check", "rationale": "Validated that patient appointment history (frequency, cancellation patterns, insurance type, lead time) provides enough signal for a reasonable no-show model."}, {"step": 4, "action": "Persona research", "rationale": "Identified three distinct buyer types with different ROI motivations: growth, efficiency, and exit planning."}, {"step": 5, "action": "Pricing architecture", "rationale": "Anchored pricing to labor savings rather than feature count; a $249/mo tool that saves $3,000/mo in staff time is an easy approval."}, {"step": 6, "action": "Risk prioritization", "rationale": "ML cold-start problem is the highest near-term risk; mitigated by shipping rule-based first and graduating to ML after sufficient data accumulates."}]',
 'submitted', 38,
 NOW() - INTERVAL '22 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '22 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '22 days');

